The 28-year-old chef, who recently moved to San Francisco, was found dead in a stairwell of a local mall this week.
However, the victim’s brother says that he can’t imagine someone who would want to hurt him, noting: “Finally his business went smoothly.”
“The body, found in Westfield Mall on Wednesday morning, was identified as a 28-year-old resident of San Francisco Frank Galicia,” the San Francisco forensics office said in a statement.
The San Francisco Police Department says the death has been classified as murder and the investigation is ongoing.
The victim’s brother, Luis Galicia, told ABC’s KGO in San Francisco that Frank, a past chef at Boston’s distribution line, got his dream job as a chef at San Francisco’s Sons & Daughters restaurant six months ago.
Sons & Daughters said they were "shocked and suppressed" by his death.
"We are a small team that works as a friendly family and will miss him very much," he said.
Our thoughts and condolences to Frank’s family and friends during this difficult time.
Luis Galicia said that Frank first stopped at the hostels, but recently “Finally his business went smoothly.”
“He found the apartment, he met the girl,” Luis Galicia told KGO.
Luis Galicia said he couldn’t imagine someone who wanted to hurt his younger brother.
He had a good heart and a good heart.
His way of connecting with the family was always to prepare us some food, to prepare us dinner,” said Luis Galicia.
He never wanted to be involved in any dispute.
He was the brother who was swimming in the stream.
“Despite all the bad things that are happening to this world, it was that limitless diamond that was shining brightly every day,” he said.
All those who possess information are requested to call the SFPD Hotline at 415-575-4444.
