The size of Italy’s government debt has increased to record figures
Italy’s government debt in June 2016 exceeded 2,248 trillion euros.
The central bank of the country said that this amount is a historical maximum, RIA Novosti reports.
The previous negative record was set in May of this year.
At that time, the amount of the state debt reached 2.228 trillion euros.
It is noted that in the first half of the year, Italy’s debt burden increased by 77.2 billion euros.
It was previously reported that at the end of 2015, Italy’s government debt amounted to 132.7% of the country’s GDP.
Meanwhile, the Italian Minister of Economy and Finance, Pier Carlo Padoan, predicted a decrease of this figure in 2016 to 130.9%, and in 2018 to 123.4% of GDP.
