Former FSIN Director has been put on trial
The Prosecutor’s Office of Moscow has approved an indictment on the investigated CSU of the SCR criminal case on the theft of budget funds allocated to the needs of FSIN of Russia.
The former head of the prison department Alexander Reimer and his deputy will be present before the court, which caused FSIN damage in the amount of more than 2.7 billion rubles.
The Capital Prosecutor’s Office sent a criminal case against the former Director of FSIN of Russia Alexander Reimer, his former Deputy Nikolai Kryvolakova, as well as the Director of the FGUP “Center for Information and Technical Services” of the Russian Federation.
Depending on the role and the degree of participation in the crime, they are accused of scoundrels in Moscow according to Art. 3, 285 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of official powers, causing serious consequences), Art. 4, 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of bribery, bribery, bribery).
In addition, Krivolapov is charged under Art. 1 of Art. 222 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the version of the SCR, in 2010-2012, these persons fraudulently stole from the state execution budget funds allocated to FSIN to provide the department with electronic monitoring systems of controlled persons, the so-called electronic bracelets.
For the theft of budget money, the participants of the group developed a scheme according to which they controlled the enterprise FGUP CITOS, with which the relevant state contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision, including "electronic bracelets", for the price, and in real estate.
Despite the fact that FGUP CITOS did not have production equipment, buildings, facilities for the placement of production facilities, allowing to create a completed cycle of production of "electronic bracelets", between him and FSIN of Russia were concluded five state contracts in the amount of more than 3.3 billion rubles.
As a result of this scheme, more than 2 billion rubles were deposited in the accounts of the Samaritan branch of the FGUP, of which 1.2 billion rubles were stolen.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles of cash paid was received personally by Mr. Reimer in his office from one of the accomplices, the criminal case in respect of which is allocated to a separate production.
Nikolay Kryvolakova, who was involved in the machinations, was found of unknown origin of the cartridge to the prize gun, which allowed him to present an additional charge.
In this case, the amount of which amounted to 133 volumes, FSIN filed a claim against the accused for compensation of material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion rubles.
