"Generation Protests" in Ethiopia, a long-time U.S. ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Protesters calling for political change in Ethiopia have faced fierce opposition from the government. . . .
Witnesses say dozens of protesters were mortally wounded during clashes with police, according to the report.
Is Ethiopia really on the verge of a split?
Over the past decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a strong ally of the West with a rapidly developing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have shocked the country, spreading to an increasing number of its territories.
In the last week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets demanding radical political change.
According to human rights defenders, the government’s reaction was brutal.
Witnesses claimed that police officers had shot dozens of unarmed protesters in the area.
Video footage from protest sites allegedly taken at the end of last year or earlier this year shows how security officers punch young people with sticks when they put their hands against the wall.
The United Nations High Representative for Human Rights is now calling for a thorough investigation.
“It has always been difficult to keep this country from collapsing, and it will be even more difficult,” said Rashid Abdi, head of the African Horn project in an international research crisis group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is supported by the West.
U.S. military and intelligence services are working closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
Ethiopia’s economy is developing at an impressive pace.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly – there is even a new suburban train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And its streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly an example of democracy — human rights organizations are constantly talking about government repressions — the opposition on the territory of the state was cut off, because dissidents were actually silenced.
Many of them were sent to prison, killed, or driven into distant deserts.
But that can change.
“If people are constantly oppressed and left with no choice but to protest, there will be an uprising,” said Seyum Teshome, a lecturer at the University of Central Ethiopia.
All the youth are protesting.
The generation is protesting.
Complaints are numerous, starting with land use, ending with the seizure of power by the government coalition.
After a widely criticized election last year, the government’s party and its allies have completely pushed out the opposition and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tension along the border with Eritrea is growing; the struggle for this uncertain, disputed border took hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less destroyed in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to use unrest and re-arm themselves.
A number of factors explain why the bitter feelings, which have been burning in the depths of the soul for several years, are now bursting.
The first, it would seem, is completely harmless: smartphones.
Only in the last couple of years has a large number of ethiopians been able to communicate on social networks, as cheap smartphones have become commonplace, and internet service has become better.
Even when the government shuts down access to Facebook and Twitter as it often happens, especially during protests, many people still find it possible to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that this is how they organized themselves for the protests.
The second is that there is more solidarity between Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
The Oromo and the Amhara are not natural allies.
Over the centuries, Amhara from predominantly Christian highlands of Ethiopia flourished in politics and business, exploiting Oromo, many of whom are Muslims and living in low-lying areas.
But it also changes.
“We will act together at the same time,” said the leader of Oromo.
The largest protests took place in the areas of Amhara and Oromo.
Many of the Amhara and Oromo feel that members of the ethnic group Tigray are unfairly dominated in Ethiopia, which makes up about 6 per cent of the population and controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third cause of anxiety is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia’s prime minister for 17 years, until his death from an unknown illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts claim that he particularly skillfully recognized the first signals of dissatisfaction and used scouts to obtain data and disarm opponents.
“The current regime lacks common sense,” said Abdi, an analyst on conflict situations.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Hailemariam Desalen, appeared from nowhere and took the place of Meles.
Unlike Meles, which was native to the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Heylemariam is a southerner.
Analysts say he does not trust the security services controlled by the Tigers.
Many fear that this will lead to even more bloodshed as a result.
Ethiopia last experienced such unrest in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts said was apparently an election that the government closed down and then falsified the results.
During the ensuing repressions, many Protestants were killed, although in smaller numbers than in recent months, and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
The development experts expressed their appreciation to the leaders of Ethiopia for the long-term development of infrastructure, such as the new intercity train and significant progress in the fight against poverty.
But it is clear that this did not stop the increase in internal discontent by the Ethiopian government.
And it takes a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, the city of Amharic, attacked businesses owned by Tigray, and anti-Tygrayan hatred on social media became widespread.
Analysts say the protesters are putting the United States and other Western allies in an awkward position.
The U.S. government has used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned flights over neighboring Somalia, although it has recently announced that it has closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand, it does not want its ally to lose power in an already unstable region.
"And it will be difficult to get through this stretchy canal," Abdi said.
