Scientists have previously assumed that the small speed of Venus' rotation is due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulation suggests that Venus was likely to have a cut-off atmosphere, similar to Earth’s, and still rotate slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of early Venus.
There were probably more dry regions on the planet than on Earth, but once there was enough water and enough geographic variability to create conditions for life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus was also in favor of the sun, which was 30 percent thicker.
“According to the GISS model, the slow rotation of Venus sets its daytime side to the sun almost every two months at a time,” Anthony Del Henio, a GISS scientist, said in a press release.
This heats the planet's surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds acting as an umbrella that protects the planet's surface from a substantial part of the sun's heat.
The result is average climate temperatures, which, surprisingly, are a few degrees cooler than they are today on Earth.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development previously assumed by experts in the study of planets.
Despite the fact that Venus may have once been habitable, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated, and its water vapor was burned by ultraviolet radiation.
