Many stars in the cluster are now only reaching maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They're spinning as fast as they'll ever be again.
At their peak rotational speeds, these adult stars throw out large amounts of stellar wind.
While traveling through the magnetic fields of the stars, these winds exert a braking effect on the stars.
As the star ages, its rotational speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of each star, tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable starspots – such as solar spots.
The latest catalog of rotational speeds suggests that more massive stars are rotating at a slower rate than less massive stars.
Fishing compares the stars to the dancers: larger ones make the pirouettes slower than smaller ones.
“In ballet, we observe that those that rotate slowly are usually more massive, while those that rotate faster are usually considered to be very light stars,” Riball said.
Since the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as the perfect space laboratory to compare the properties of stars to the speed of rotation.
“The Pleiades star cluster provides a starting point for theoretical models of the rotation of stars, both younger and older,” Riball said.
